\subsubsection{Okamoto-rename of the V$_{\mathrm{quad}}$ parameter
point: $(\eta, \theta) \to (\alpha, \beta)$}
\label{ssec:okamoto-rename}

The $\Vquad \rightsquigarrow P_{III}(D_6)$ identification at
parameter point $(1/6, 0, 0, -1/2)$
(\Cref{ssec:cc}, lines~127--131; \cite{iwasaki1991from,
ohyama2006studies}) is stated in a 4-tuple convention
$(\alpha_\infty, \alpha_0, \beta_\infty, \beta_0)$ that does
not appear in Okamoto's original Hamiltonian
\cite[\S 1.1]{okamoto1987painleveIII}, where the canonical
parameters are $(\eta_\infty, \eta_0, \theta_\infty, \theta_0)$.
The present sub-subsection records the explicit rename used
throughout this paper to bridge the two conventions.

\paragraph{Okamoto's canonical parameters.}
The Hamiltonian for $P_{III}$ in
\cite[\S 1.1, p.~306, eq.~(0.0)]{okamoto1987painleveIII} reads
\[
H_{III} \;=\;
\frac{1}{t}\Bigl[2 q^{2} p^{2} - \bigl\{2 \eta_\infty\, t q^{2}
+ (2 \theta_0 + 1) q - 2 \eta_0\, t\bigr\} p
+ \eta_\infty (\theta_0 + \theta_\infty) t q\Bigr],
\]
with the standing convention $\eta_0, \eta_\infty \neq 0$ and
the WLOG normalisation $\eta_0 = \eta_\infty = 1$ adopted in
\cite[\S 1.1, p.~306]{okamoto1987painleveIII}. Under this
normalisation the four-parameter family $(\eta_\infty, \eta_0,
\theta_\infty, \theta_0)$ collapses to the two free monodromy
parameters $(\theta_\infty, \theta_0)$ at infinity and at the
origin, with $\eta_\infty, \eta_0$ the two non-zero scales.

\paragraph{Project rename to $(\alpha, \beta)$.}
The project's 4-tuple $(\alpha_\infty, \alpha_0, \beta_\infty,
\beta_0)$ is related to Okamoto's $(\eta_\infty, \eta_0,
\theta_\infty, \theta_0)$ by\footnote{%
The symbol $(\alpha, \beta)$ in this sub-subsection denotes
the Okamoto-rename 4-tuple of monodromy parameters introduced
here. It is independent of (i) the WKB exponents $(A, \alpha,
\beta, \gamma)$ of \Cref{prop:wkb} (\Cref{ssec:wkb}), and (ii)
the classical $P_{III}$ ODE coefficients $(\alpha, \beta,
\gamma, \delta)$ of \cite[eq.~(0.1)]{okamoto1987painleveIII}.
We use subscripts $\infty, 0$ throughout to disambiguate the
present 4-tuple from those two.}
